==Subgenres==
[[File:Congo Natty 2.jpg|thumb|140px|Congo Natty, a ragga jungle artist]]
Smaller scenes within the drum and bass community have developed and the scene as a whole has become much more fractured into specific subgenres, including:
* Drumstep or Halftime is a combination of drum and bass and dubstep where the beat structure is [[half-time (music)|half time]], while the remaining elements still adhere to the usual sub-bass and tempo of drum and bass.<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://producingelectronicmusic.com/2012/12/07/dubstep-drumstep-and-dnb/| title=Dubstep, Drumstep, and DNB| work=Brad Bator| number=| date=31 March 2011| accessdate=31 July 2015}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://news.beatport.com/wtf-is-drumstep/ | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150903220453/https://news.beatport.com/wtf-is-drumstep/ | dead-url=yes | archive-date=3 September 2015 | title=WTF is Drumstep? | work=The Beatport Team | number= | date=4 February 2011 | accessdate=31 July 2015 }}</ref>
* [[Breakcore]] is a style of electronic dance music largely influenced by hardcore, jungle, digital hardcore and industrial music that is characterized by its use of heavy kick drums, breaks and a wide palette of sampling sources, played at high tempos.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}
* [[Ragga jungle|Ragga drum & bass]] was inspired by the original [[ragga jungle]] style, with influences from [[reggae]] and [[dancehall]] music. Notable artists include [[Shy FX]], [[T Power]], Congo Natty, Potential Bad Boy, Marcus Visionary, Serial Killaz, Ed Solo, Deekline, Isaac Maya, Run Tingz Cru, Psychofreud, Benny Page and vocalists such as David Boomah, Top Cat, Tenor Fly and General Levy.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}
* [[Hardstep]] is a harder style which uses gritty basslines and heavy yet simple electronic melodies.<ref name="globaldarkness"/> Notable artists include Dillinja (early work), DJ Krust, Mampi Swift, [[Dieselboy]], Current Value, Tre Technics, MachineCode{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}
* [[Darkstep]] is characterized by fast drums and a general dark mood, drawing influences from [[dark ambient]], [[Industrial music|industrial]] and [[Hardcore (electronic dance music genre)|hardcore]] music. Prominent artists include Technical Itch, Dylan, Kryptic Minds & Leon Switch, B-Key, Resonant Evil, Infiltrata, SPL, [[Counterstrike (drum and bass group)|Counterstrike]], Evol Intent, [[The Panacea]], [[Limewax]], and [[Current Value]].{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}
* [[Techstep]] is characterized by [[Science fiction|sci-fi]] [[soundscape]]s<ref name="SimonReynoldsOnTechstep">{{Cite book|last = Reynolds|first = Simon|title = Energy Flash: A Journey Through Rave Music and Dance Culture|year = 2013|publisher = Soft Skull Press|quote = Where intelligent drum and bass suffers from a obsessive-compulsive cleanliness, techstep production is deliberately dirty, all dense murk and noxious drones.|accessdate = 1 June 2014}}</ref> and samples from science fiction culture. Pioneered by artists such as [[Bad Company (drum and bass group)|Bad Company UK]] (DJ Fresh, D-Bridge, Maldini & Vegas) [[Ed Rush]], Optical, Konflict (Kemal & Rob Data), [[Dom & Roland]], Dillinja, Ram Trilogy (Ant Miles, Andy C & Shimon), Moving Fusion, Decoder & Substance, Digital & Spirit, Future Cut, Dylan, Loxy & Ink, Total Science, D.Kay, Stakka & Skynet and Keaton with Usual Suspects or Universal Project, Klute, Concord Dawn, and the label [[Moving Shadow]].<ref>{{Cite web| url= http://thewire.co.uk/in-writing/essays/the-wire-300_simon-reynolds-on-the-hardcore-continuum_4_hardstep_jump-up_techstep_1996_ | title= Slipping Into Darkness | work= The Wire |number= 148 |date= June 1996 | accessdate= 31 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|author = Chris Christodoulou|url = https://www.pneumonia.org.au/index.php/dancecult/article/download/316/310|title = Rumble in the Jungle: The Invisible History of Drum and Bass by Steven Quinn, in: Transformations, No 3 (2002)|quote = Techstep is a subgenre of drum 'n' bass characterised by harsh noise, tonal dissonance and a discourse of sonic violence.|date = 2002|accessdate = 6 April 2014|deadurl = yes|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141110183454/https://www.pneumonia.org.au/index.php/dancecult/article/download/316/310|archivedate = 10 November 2014|df = }}</ref>
* [[Neurofunk]] or Neuro is the progression from techstep<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.thewire.co.uk/in-writing/essays/the-wire-300_simon-reynolds-on-the-hardcore-continuum_5_neurofunk-drum_n_bass-versus-speed | title=2 Steps Back | work= The Wire |number= 166 |date= December 1997 | accessdate= 31 January 2013}}</ref> incorporating more elements from [[jazz]] and [[funk]]. Prominent artists include [[Ed Rush]], Matrix, Bad Company UK, Cause 4 Concern, TeeBee, Future Prophecies, Black Sun Empire, DLR, Calyx, Hive, Gridlok, Noisia, Phace & Misanthrop, Silent Witness & Break, State Of Mind, The Upbeats, Chase & Status, [[Jade (drum and bass producer)|Jade]], Mindscape, [[Spor]], Psidream, Catacomb, Rregula and The Clamps.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}
* Jump-up, appearing in the mid-1990s,<ref name="bogdanov">{{Cite book| last=Bogdanov| first=Vladimir|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/All_Music_Guide_to_Electronica.html?id=GJNXLSBlL7IC&redir_esc=y|title=All music guide to electronica: the definitive guide to electronica| pages= 225, 638, 140| year= 2001| publisher=[[Rough Guides]]|isbn=1858284333}}</ref> employs heavy and energetic drum and bass,<ref name="bogdanov"/> characterized by robotic and heavy bass sounds. It also is generally less serious and contains more humor than other subgenres. Notable artists include [[DJ Hazard (musician)|DJ Hazard]], Generation Dub (Original Sin & Sub Zero), Baron, Cabbie, Clipz, Nightwalker, Callide, Hedex, Epsy, Taxman, Jaydan, Sub Zero, Original Sin, Annix, Konichi, Decimal Bass, Spaow, Nu Elementz, Tyke, DJ Zen, Majistrate,<ref name="ishkurOnJumpUp">{{Cite web|author = Ishkur|url = http://techno.org/electronic-music-guide/jumpup.swf
|title = Ishkur's guide to Electronic Music|date = 2005|accessdate = 1 June 2014}}</ref> Twisted Individual, Distorted Minds, TC, Heist, DJ Guv, Looney, Premium, Upgrade, DJ Pleasure, [[DJ Hype]]<ref>{{Cite book|last = Reynolds|first = Simon|title = Energy Flash: A Journey Through Rave Music and Dance Culture|year = 2013|publisher = Soft Skull Press|quote = At clubs like AWOL, the ruling sound is the gangsta hard-step and 'jump up' jungle of labels like Ganja, Frontline, Dread, Suburban Base and Dope Dragon, made by DJ&mdash;producers like Hype, Pascal, Andy C, Ray Keith, L. Double, Shy FX...|accessdate = 1 June 2014}}</ref> and his label Playaz Recordings.
* Ambient drum & bass, Atmospheric drum & bass, Intelligent drum & bass, Jazzy drum and bass or Intelligent jungle is a smoother style, influenced by [[ambient music]], [[Chill-out music|chillout]], [[jazz]] and [[Soul music]]. It was pioneered by such artists as [[Omni Trio]], Foul Play, [[Seba (musician)|Seba]], [[Blu Mar Ten]], Nookie, Hyper-On-Experience, DJ Pulse, Higher Sense, [[Deep Blue (musician)|Deep Blue]] (Sean O'Keefe, Cause4Concern Records), [[Photek]], [[Jack Smooth]] (Basement Records), Blame,<ref name="ishkurOnAtmosphericDrumAndBass">{{Cite web|author = Ishkur|url = http://techno.org/electronic-music-guide/atmosphericjungle.swf|title = Atmospheric drum and bass|date = 2005|accessdate = 1 June 2014}}</ref> [[LTJ Bukem]]<ref name="ishkurOnAtmosphericDrumAndBass"/> and his label [[Good Looking Records]],<ref name="globaldarkness"/> and the label [[Moving Shadow]].
* Jazzstep or Jazzy jungle demonstrates heavy influence by [[jazz]]. It uses typical jazz scales, rhythms and instrumentation. Notable artists include Roni size & Reprazent,<ref name="ishkurOnJazzstep">{{Cite web|author = Ishkur|url = http://techno.org/electronic-music-guide/jazzstep.swf|title = Jazz step
|date = 2005|accessdate = 1 June 2014}}</ref> Goldie,<ref name="ishkurOnJazzstep"/> Utah Jazz,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/21340-Utah-Jazz|title=Utah Jazz|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=15 February 2017}}</ref> Morgan Sullyvan, [[Makoto (artist)|Makoto]], [[Alex Reece]],<ref name="globaldarkness"/> and [[DJ Dextrous]].
* [[Liquid funk]] (or simply Liquid) draws heavily on harmonic and melodic grooves, and samples from [[funk]], [[jazz]], [[Soul music|soul]], [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[disco]], [[House music|house]] and [[breakbeat]], while [[intelligent drum and bass]] or [[atmospheric drum and bass]] creates a calmer yet more synthetic sound. It was pioneered by Calibre,<ref name="ishkurOnliquidFunk">{{Cite web|author = Ishkur|url = http://techno.org/electronic-music-guide/liquidfunk.swf|title = Liquid funk|date = 2005
|accessdate = 1 June 2014}}</ref> Zero Tolerance (Zero T) & Beta 2, [[London Elektricity]],<ref name="ishkurOnliquidFunk"/> High Contrast,<ref name="ishkurOnliquidFunk"/> Logistics, [[Nu:Tone]],<ref name="ishkurOnliquidFunk"/> Danny Byrd, [[Cyantific]], [[Netsky (musician)|Netsky]], Lenzman, Technimatic (Technicolour & Komatic), Hobzee & Zyon Base, Paul T & Edward Oberon, Hybrid Minds and labels such as [[Hospital Records]], Fokuz Records and Liquid V. The first Liquid only events were Liquidiser at Bristol Academy.
* [[Sambass]] (or Brazilian drum and bass) incorporates elements from [[samba]], [[bossa nova]] and other [[Latin music (genre)|Latin music]] styles. Pioneered by artists such as [[DJ Marky]],<ref>{{Cite web|author = Chris Christodoulou|url = https://www.pneumonia.org.au/index.php/dancecult/article/download/316/310|title = Rumble in the Jungle: The Invisible History of Drum and Bass by Steven Quinn, in: Transformations, No 3 (2002)|quote = the popularity of the sambass subgenre, exported to the dance clubs and pop charts of the UK by Brazil's DJ Marky in the mid-2000s, or the Asian drum 'n' breaks scene, which draws on classical Indian music, bhangra and Bollywood film soundtracks.|date = 2002|accessdate = 1 June 2014|deadurl = yes|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141110183454/https://www.pneumonia.org.au/index.php/dancecult/article/download/316/310|archivedate = 10 November 2014|df = }}</ref> [[Xerxes de Oliveira|XRS]], [[DJ Patife]] and Bryan Gee's label.
* [[Drill 'n' bass]] (also known as Fungle and Spunk jazz) incorporates double-time drum 'n' bass with undanceable rhythms, low-brow humor, and ambient vibes.<ref>{{cite book| last= Shapiro| first=Peter|authorlink=Peter Shapiro (journalist)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IxEpAyPvyXoC&pg=PT175#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Drum 'n' Bass: The Rough Guide| page= 207| date= 1 August 1999| publisher=[[Rough Guides]]|isbn=1858284333}}</ref> The subgenre was developed by [[Squarepusher]] and [[Aphex Twin]], whose rapid and irregularly [[syncopation|syncopated]] basslines discouraged dancing. Other pioneers include [[Bogdan Raczynski]] and Datach'i.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Tzc8m4fJvlwC&pg=PA161#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Wired for Sound: Engineering and Technologies in Sonic Cultures | page= 161| editor1-first= Paul D. | editor1-last= Greene | editor2-first= Thomas | editor2-last= Porcello| publisher=[[Wesleyan University Press]]| date= 1 March 2010|isbn=0819565164}}</ref>

===Regional scenes===
Despite its roots in the UK, which can still be treated as the "home" of drum and bass, the style has firmly established itself around the world. There are strong scenes in other English-speaking countries including Australia, Canada, South Africa, the United States and, New Zealand.<ref>"Drum & Bass Keeps The Beat", ''Boston Globe'', 6 February 2003.</ref> It is popular throughout continental Europe, and in South America. [[São Paulo]] is sometimes called the drum and bass [[Ibiza]].{{citation needed|date=May 2013}} Brazilian drum and bass is sometimes referred to as "[[sambass]]", with its specific style and sound. In Venezuela and Mexico, artists have created their own forms of drum and bass combining it with experimental musical forms. In Colombia there is a large underground scene, The RE.set Label and Bogotá Project are two collectives that put on DnB events in the city, as well as a twice yearly event called Radikal Styles, that brings together local talent and international big names.

Austria has a large emerging DnB scene with many artists such as Camo & Krooked, Mefjus, Fourward, Body & Soul, IllSkillz and mainly the Mainframe record label being all based in or around Vienna. Notable venues and events include The Hive and Beat It at Flex held almost every Thursday and Saturday, Vollkontakt at Fluc, Switch at Flex and the monthly Mainframe Recordings Label-Night hosted at Arena by label head Disaszt.

The Czech Republic currently hosts the largest drum and bass festival in the world, LET IT ROLL, with attendance of approximately 30,000. The genre is also encountered Slovakia, and local producers in both countries like A-Cray, Rido, Forbidden Society, L Plus, B-Complex, Changing Faces, etc. becoming well known worldwide. There are several other drum and bass festivals being held each year in these countries, including Trident Festival, Exploration Festival or Hoofbeats Open Air in the summer, or one night events such as LET IT ROLL Winter, Imagination Festival, LET IT ROLL Winter Slovakia in the colder months. During the club season, it goes without saying that promoters are racing between each other to organise better events, often resulting in 10 parties being held during one weekend with no more than 2 hour travel between them.

===Genres influenced by drum and bass===
Born around the same time as jungle, [[breakcore]] and [[digital hardcore]] share many of the elements of drum and bass and to the uninitiated, tracks from the extreme end of drum and bass may sound identical to breakcore thanks to speed, complexity, impact and maximum sonic density combined with musical experimentation. German Drum and Bass DJ [[The Panacea]] is also one of the leading Digital Hardcore artists. [[Raggacore]] resembles a faster version of the ragga influenced jungle music of the 1990s, similar to breakcore but with more friendly [[dancehall]] beats (dancehall itself being a very important influence on drum and bass).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lfodemon.com/raggacorearticle/index.htm |title=Raggacore article on lfodemon.com |accessdate=6 September 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070217064746/http://www.lfodemon.com/raggacorearticle/index.htm |archivedate=17 February 2007 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> [[Darkcore]], a direct influence on drum and bass, was combined with influences of drum and bass itself leading to the creation of [[darkstep]]. There is considerable crossover from the extreme edges of drum and bass, breakcore, darkcore, digital hardcore and raggacore with fluid boundaries.

The genre has influenced many other genres like [[hip hop]], [[big beat]], [[dubstep]], [[house music]], [[trip hop]], [[ambient music]], [[techno]], [[rock music|rock]] and [[pop music|pop]], with artists such as [[Bill Laswell]], [[Incubus (band)|Incubus]], [[Pitchshifter (band)|Pitchshifter]], [[Linkin Park]], [[The Roots]], [[Talvin Singh]], [[MIDIval Punditz]], [[Missy Elliott]], [[The Freestylers]], [[Bowery Electric]], [[Nine Inch Nails]], [[David Bowie]] (the last two both using elements of Goldie's "Timeless"){{Citation needed|date=October 2014}} and others quoting drum and bass and using drum and bass techniques and elements. Recently created in the United States is a genre called [[ghettotech]] which contains synth and basslines similar to drum & bass.<ref name="Fabio3">{{Cite web| url = http://www.redbullmusicacademy.com/TUTORS.9.0.html?act_session=290 | title = Red Bull Academy Interview Fabio – The Root To The Shoot| accessdate = 4 September 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080420135102/http://www.redbullmusicacademy.com/TUTORS.9.0.html?act_session=290|archivedate=20 April 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.knowledgemag.co.uk/features.asp?ReviewID=1278&PageNumber=1&SectionID=1031 | title = A Guy Called Gerald feature at knowledgemag.co.uk | accessdate = 6 September 2006 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/61H1WFDEp?url=http://www.knowledgemag.co.uk/features.asp?ReviewID=1278&PageNumber=1&SectionID=1031 | archivedate = 28 August 2011 | df =  }}</ref><ref name="Playford">{{Cite web | url = http://remixmag.com/mag/remix_drumnbasspioneer_rob_playford/ | title = Remix Mag Interview with Rob Playford, drum and bass pioneer at remixmag.com | accessdate = 5 October 2006 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070207105625/http://remixmag.com/mag/remix_drumnbasspioneer_rob_playford/ | archivedate = 7 February 2007 | df =  }}</ref><ref name="Popular">{{Cite web| url = http://www.popular-musicology-online.com/issues/02/missingham.html | title = "Popular Musicology On Line Article "Big Tings Ah Gwan": Junglist Music Takes Centre Stage, An Introduction to Jungle Music And An Enquiry Into Its Impact On The London Jazz Scene"| accessdate = 4 September 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web| url = {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p24040/biography|pure_url=yes}} | title = Pitchshifter biography| accessdate = 16 May 2009}}</ref>

