==Record labels==
{{See also|Category:Drum and bass record labels}}

Drum and Bass is dominated by a small group of record labels. These are run mainly by DJ–producers, such as [[London Elektricity]]'s [[Hospital Records]], [[Andy C]] and Scott Bourne's [[Ram Records (UK)|RAM]],<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ramrecords.com/info#label-history|title=RAM Records|last=|first=|date=|website=RAM Records|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref> [[Goldie]]'s [[Metalheadz]], Kasra's [[Critical Music]], Basement Records ([[Jack Smooth]]), [[DJ Friction (UK)|DJ Friction]]'s Shogun Audio,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shogunaudio.co.uk/about-us.php|title=About Us|website=Shogun Audio|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120716040539/http://www.shogunaudio.co.uk/about-us.php|archivedate=16 July 2012|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref> [[DJ Fresh]]'s [[Breakbeat Kaos]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redbull.com/gb-en/drum-and-bass-still-on-top|title=Eternal evolution: why drum’n’bass refuses to die|last=|first=|date=|website=www.redbull.com|language=en|access-date=5 October 2017}}</ref> [[Futurebound]]'s Viper Recordings and [[DJ Hype]], Pascal, [[NoCopyrightSounds]] and formerly [[DJ Zinc]]'s [[True Playaz]] (now known as Real Playaz as of 2006).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/playazrecordings?sk=info|title=Playaz Recordings - About|website=Facebook}}</ref>

Prior to 2016, the major international music labels such as [[Sony Music]] and [[Universal Music Group|Universal]] had shown very little interest in the drum and bass scene, with the exception of some notable signings, including [[Pendulum (drum and bass band)|Pendulum]]'s ''[[In Silico (Pendulum album)|In Silico]]'' LP to Warner. Roni Size's label played a big, if not the biggest, part in the creation of drum and bass with their dark, baseline sounds. V Recordings also played a large part of the development of drum and bass.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nesthq.com/premiere-bryan-gee-interview|title=V Recordings' Bryan Gee Discusses History and Future of Drum & Bass + Premieres Intelligent Manners' "How Sweet It Is"|date=12 August 2016|publisher=NEST HQ|first=Nathan|last=Beer}}</ref> Roni Size, Krust and DJ Die produced some of the first tracks to be considered{{who|date=March 2015}} mainstream drum and bass tracks.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}

[[BMG Rights Management]] acquired [[Ram Records (UK)|Ram Records]] in February 2016,<ref name="bmg.com"/> making a strategic investment to help RAM Records (a London-based drum and bass record company co-owned by [[Andy C]] and his business partner Scott Bourne). RAM Records has been pushing the boundaries of drum and bass further into the mainstream with artists such as [[Chase and Status]] and [[Sub Focus]].<ref name=":0" /> Bringing back UK [[Oldschool jungle|jungle music]] artists from [[LTJ Bukem]]'s label [[Good Looking]] artists Bay B Kane, [[breakbeat hardcore]] heavyweight Nebula II and original [[junglist]] Gappa G. Other Bristol labels such as Cafe Bass have also helped to push through a sound categorised as 'bass music' with the help of influential artists such as Lone Ranger.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}

Now defunct labels, include [[Rob Playford]]'s [[Moving Shadow]], running from 1990 until 2007, which played a pivotal role in the nineties drum and bass scene, releasing records by artists such as [[Omni Trio]].

==Formats and distribution==

===Purchasing===
Originally drum and bass was mostly sold in 12-inch [[vinyl record|vinyl]] single format. With the emergence of drum and bass into mainstream music markets, more albums, compilations and [[DJ mixes]] started to be sold on CDs. As digital music became more popular, websites focused on electronic music, such as [[Beatport]], began to sell drum and bass in digital format.

===Distributors (wholesale)===
The bulk of drum and bass vinyl records and CDs are distributed globally and regionally by a relatively small number of companies such as SRD (Southern Record Distributors), ST Holdings, & Nu Urban.<ref>{{Cite web| url = http://www.knowledgemag.co.uk/features.asp?ReviewID=1574&PageNumber=1&SectionID=1031 | title = Distribution feature at knowledgemag.co.uk| accessdate = 6 September 2006}}</ref>

As of 11 September 2012, Nu Urban Music Limited ceased trading and RSM Tenon were instructed to assist in convening statutory meetings of members and creditors to appoint a liquidator. This left many labels short on sales as Nu Urban were one of the main Distributors for the vinyl market in the drum and bass scene.<ref>{{Cite web| url = http://www.nu-urbanmusic.co.uk | title = Announcement of bankruptcy on nu-urbanmusic.co.uk | accessdate = 21 September 2012}}</ref>

==Media presence==
Today, drum and bass is widely promoted throughout the world using different methods such as [[video sharing service]]s ([[YouTube]], [[Dailymotion]]), [[blog]]s, [[radio]] and [[television]], the latter being the most uncommon method. More recently, music networking websites such as [[SoundCloud]] and MixCloud have become powerful tools for artist recognition, providing a vast platform that enables quick responses to new tracks. Record labels have adopted the use of [[Podcast]]s. Prior to the rise of the internet, drum and bass was commonly broadcast over [[pirate radio]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fantazia.org.uk/radio/pirateradio_timeline.htm|title=Pirate Radio Stations - A Brief Timeline of the UK scene|website=www.fantazia.org.uk|access-date=15 February 2017}}</ref>

===Radio===
The three highest profile radio stations playing drum and bass shows are [[BBC Radio 1]] with The Drum and Bass Show - formerly with [[DJ Friction (UK)|Friction]], who was replaced with [[René LaVice]] in 2017,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ukf.com/news/friction-announces-departure-from-radio-1-1xtra-rene-lavice-to-takeover-from-november/20518|title=Friction announces departure from Radio 1 & 1Xtra, Rene LaVice to takeover from November|website=www.ukf.com|access-date=8 January 2018}}</ref> simulcast in the US and Canada on Sirius XM, and [[DJ Hype]] on [[Kiss 100 London|Kiss 100]] in London. Fabio and Grooverider previously held a long-standing drum and bass show on Radio 1, and there was also Radio 1's 'One in the Jungle' show.

The BBC's "urban" station [[BBC Radio 1Xtra]] used to feature the genre heavily, with DJ Bailey (show axed as of 29 August 2012) and Crissy Criss (show axed as of August 2014<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b04f8m00|title=27/08/2014, D&B with Crissy Criss - BBC Radio 1Xtra|website=BBC|access-date=15 February 2017}}</ref>) as its advocates. The network also organises a week-long tour of the UK each year called [[Xtra Bass]]. London pirate radio stations have been instrumental in the development of Drum and Bass, with stations such as [[Kool FM]] (which continues to broadcast today having done so since 1991), Origin FM, [[Don FM]] (the only Drum and Bass pirate to have gained a temporary legal license), [http://www.renegaderadio.co.uk Renegade Radio 107.2FM], Rude FM, Wax Fm and Eruption among the most influential.

As of 2014, despite higher profile stations such as 1Xtra scaling back their drum and bass specialist coverage, the genre has made its way into UK top 10 charts with drum and bass inspired tracks from artists such as Rudimental and Sigma. Earlier in August 2014, before Crissy Criss' show was axed, the BBC held a whole prime time evening event dedicated to showcasing drum and bass by allowing four major labels to participate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b04dm0p1|title=D&B Soundclash Special, MistaJam - BBC Radio 1Xtra|website=BBC|access-date=15 February 2017}}</ref>

As of November 2014, there have been 6 drum & bass songs reaching the no.1 spot on the UK's top 40 chart, since the genre was first being played on the radio, around 1993. The first of these was in 2012. The fact that all 6 of these songs have reached number 1 in only two years shows the increase in popularity and commercialisation of the genre in recent years. The artists that produced these songs are [[Sigma (group)|Sigma]], [[Rudimental]] and [[DJ Fresh]] (all have had two No.1 hits).

====Internet radio====
Internet radio stations, acting in the same light as pirate stations, have also been an instrumental part in promoting drum and bass music; the majority of them funded by listener and artist donations.

Drum and bass was supported by [[Ministry of Sound]] radio from the early 2000s until 2014 and later featuring Tuesday shows from labels such as [[Metalheadz]], [[Fabio]] & [[Grooverider]], [[DJ Marky]], Viper Recordings, [[Shogun Audio]] and [[Hospital Records]]. From September 2014, Ministry abruptly dropped all non-mainstream genres to focus on mainstream EDM, causing disappointment amongst the fans of the D&B community.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Steven|first1=Colin|title=Ministry Of Sound Radio Drops Drum & Bass|url=http://kmag.uk/ministry-of-sound-radio-drops-drum-bass/|website=K Mag}}</ref>

====North American Radio====
In North America, The Prophecy on 89.5 [[CIUT-FM]] With Marcus Visionary, DJ Prime and Mr. Brown Is North America's longest running Jungle Radio show{{citation needed|date=March 2015}} (Toronto), Album 88.5 (Atlanta) and [[KNHC|C89.5fm]] (Seattle) have shows showcasing drum and bass. In New York, "DNB NYC RADIO" show with Host Dj Benzocaine on 90.3 [[WHCR-FM]] has a weekly 3 hour show which broadcasts in New York and New Jersey which plays only Drum and Bass every Thursday starting at 3{{nbsp}} am. "DNB NYC RADIO" is the only weekly Drum and Bass show on the FM dial in Northeastern United States. Seattle also has a long-standing electronica show known as Expansions on 90.3 FM KEXP. The rotating DJs include Kid Hops, whose shows are made up mostly of drum and bass. In Columbus, Ohio WCBE 90.5 has a two-hour electronic only showcase, "All Mixed Up," Saturday nights at 10{{nbsp}}pm. At the same time WUFM 88.7 plays its "Electronic Playground." Also, [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]]'s rock station, 104.5 The Edge, has a two-hour show starting at 10{{nbsp}}pm Saturday nights called Edge Essential Mix mixed by DJ Demko showcasing electronic and drum and bass style. While the aforementioned shows in Ohio rarely play drum and bass the latter plays the genre with some frequency. In [[Tucson, Arizona]], 91.3 FM [[KXCI]] has a two-hour electronic show known as "Digital Empire", Friday nights at 10{{nbsp}}pm (MST). Resident DJ Trinidad showcases various styles of electronica, with the main focus being drum and bass, jungle & [[dubstep]]. In [[Augusta, Georgia]], [[zarbizarre]] of the [[Cereal Killaz]] hosts a show called FreQuency on [[WHHD]] on Friday nights from 11{{nbsp}}pm until 1{{nbsp}}am, showcasing drum and bass during the 2nd hour of the show.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hd983.com/frequency/|title=FreQuency on HD - HD98.3|website=hd983.com|language=en-US|access-date=15 February 2017}}</ref>

===Magazines===
The best-known drum and bass publication was [http://www.kmag.uk ''Kmag''] magazine (formerly called ''Knowledge Magazine'') before it went completely online in August 2009. Although it's still live, after 20 years Kmag ceased updating their site at the end of 2014. Kmag's publishing arm Vision, published Brian Belle-Fortune's All Crews Journeys Through Jungle Drum & Bass Culture in 2004.

Other publications include the longest running drum and bass magazine worldwide, ''ATM Magazine'', and Austrian-based ''[[Resident (magazine)|Resident]]''. London-based ''DJ'' magazine has also been running a widely respected drum and bass reviews page since 1993, written by Alex Constantinides, which many followers refer to when seeking out new releases to investigate. In 2012 Alex stopped writing the reviews and they are now contributed by Whisky Kicks.

